	<script src="http://www.independent.co.uk/independent.co.uk/editorial/web/adsense/show_ads.js"></script>

<!-- adSurroundClose -->
<p>

	<div class="body">
		<!-- Check if it is the money section -->
        <p>
			</p>

		<p>
<b>Gravy</b>
</p>
<p>
When the Royal Society of Chemistry wanted to find the perfect gravy recipe as 
  part of their 2009 Year of Food project, they went to Yorkshireman and 
  chemist John Emsley. He uses all the elements of a traditional roast to make 
  his gravy, from the meat juices to the water the vegetables are boiled in, 
  which add nutrients as well as flavour. &ldquo;The perfect way to do the Sunday 
  meal is with gravy from the joint. Why waste the nutrients?&rdquo; he says.
</p>
<p>
Start by cooking the joint on a bed of halved onions, carrots and celery, 
  which juices from the meat will slowly trickle on to. When the meat is 
  cooked, remove it from the roasting tin along with the vegetables. Sprinkle 
  a small amount of plain flour over the meat juices and fat. 
</p>
<div class="related-articles">
	<h2>Related articles</h2>
	<ul class="">
	<li >
			<a href="http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/recipes/around-the-world-in-80-dishes-no4-greece-1962377.html" target="">
				Around the world in 80 dishes No.4: Greece</a>
		</li>
	<li class="search">
				<a href="http://www.news-archive.independent.co.uk/" target="_blank">Search the news archive for more stories</a>
			</li>
		</ul>
</div>

<p>
Stir to form a dough &ndash; or roux &ndash; by gradually adding the water you&rsquo;ve boiled 
  your accompanying vegetables in. John says it works best with cabbage water. 
  &ldquo;If you boil things like cabbage, you lose nutrients into the water. Using 
  that water in the gravy adds an extra little depth &ndash; it&rsquo;s a way of putting 
  that back into the meal.&rdquo;
</p>
<p>
Stir the gravy until all the meat juices and Marmite-like deposits on the 
  bottom of the roasting dish have dissolved. Add iodised salt to taste and a 
  teaspoon of soy sauce. Perhaps a surprising addition, soy sauce is a crucial 
  ingredient because it reaches our fifth taste, what the Japanese call umami. 
  Simmer to reduce the liquid to the right consistency, stirring occasionally, 
  and then pour all over your traditional roast. 
</p>
<p>
<b>Souffl</b>
</p>
<p>
Penny Lewis, who runs cookery courses at The Culinary Cottage near 
  Abergavenny, South Wales, which deal with supposedly tricky dishes, is 
  confident that anyone can make a souffl that is lovely and light. &ldquo;Most 
  people are just frightened of it,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;You do need a good whisk, and 
  a clean bowl. Have it all in place before you start, and the oven at the 
  right temperature &ndash; having the right equipment and ingredients to hand is 
  important so you can time it right.&rdquo; 
</p>
<p>
Preheat the oven to 200C. Generously butter a 15cm souffl dish and coat with 
  finely grated parmesan. Separate four large eggs. Melt 30g butter in a 
  saucepan, stir in 30g of plain flour, half a teaspoon of mustard and a pinch 
  of cayenne pepper. Cook for a minute or two, remove from the heat and stir 
  in 225ml of full-fat milk. Return it to the heat, whisking until thickened, 
  and continue to cook for a few minutes while continually whisking. 
</p>
<p>
Remove from the heat. Then stir in between 85g and 110g of either strong 
  cheddar or gruy&egrave;re cheese, followed by the egg yolks and salt and pepper. 
</p>
<p>
Whisk the egg whites in a very clean bowl until they are stiff but not dry. 
  Gently fold in the cheese mixture with a metal spoon, and pour into a 
  souffl dish. &ldquo;Run your thumb around the top edge of the dish, for the &lsquo;top 
  hat&rsquo; effect,&rdquo; suggests Penny. Bake for 25 to 30 minutes until it is golden 
  brown and well-risen. To check if your souffl is ready, open the oven door 
  slightly (but not before 20 minutes has elapsed) and give the dish &ldquo;a gentle 
  shove&rdquo; &ndash; if it just wobbles, it&rsquo;s ready; if it is very wobbly, allow five 
  more minutes.
</p>
<p>
But the real key to souffl success is to eat it quickly. Penny&rsquo;s final rule? 
  Make sure your guests are at the table and ready to eat when you get your 
  souffl out of the oven. 
</p>
<p>
<b>Basmati rice</b>
</p>
<p>
Rice is one of those basic accompaniments that we should all be able to 
  manage, yet it so often ends up sticky. We turned to Michelin-starred chef 
  Alfred Prasad, from Indian restaurant Tamarind, for his approach. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s very 
  easy,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;This method applies to all good quality rice. First, 
  measure your rice in a liquid measurement, say 500ml. Alfred insists that 
  soaking the rice &ndash; a process we might be tempted to skip &ndash; is really 
  important. &ldquo;Grains of rice rub against each in the packet, which produces a 
  starchy powder, and soaking gets rid of that,&rdquo; he says.
</p>
<p>
After 10 to 15 minutes, drain and then rinse the rice two or three times until 
  it is no longer &ldquo;milky&rdquo;. Measure your water, using double the quantity of 
  rice: one litre of water for 500ml of rice. Use a vessel at least twice its 
  volume and put the water on to boil. As soon as the water is boiling, turn 
  down the heat and throw in the soaked, rinsed rice. &ldquo;People do use salt, but 
  it&rsquo;s really not required,&rdquo; says Alfred. &ldquo;Another useful tip, which probably 
  won&rsquo;t go down well with the healthy-eating brigade, is to add a teaspoon of 
  vegetable oil to keep the rice from sticking.&rdquo;
</p>
<p>
Stir the rice a couple of times to stop it from &ldquo;clumping&rdquo; at the bottom 
  (Alfred recommends using a spatula, rather than a spoon), and bring it back 
  to the boil. &ldquo;Once you get to the point when there is no more moisture on 
  the top of the rice, but while it is still fairly wet at the bottom, turn 
  the heat off,&rdquo; he says. Alfred then leaves the pan open, without a lid, so 
  that all the excess steam can clear. Leave for 10 minutes, then transfer to 
  your serving dish. 
</p>
<p>
<b>Meringues</b>
</p>
<p>
We all dream of fluffy, cloud-like creations with outer crunch and inner goo, 
  but may find ourselves brought back down to earth with browned, flattened 
  lumps. Lynn Bolton has mastered the art, and has up a mail-order meringue 
  company, Head in the Clouds, dedicated to selling her confections. She 
  shares her secrets for the classic meringue nest.
</p>
<p>
&ldquo;Ensure you have clean bowls and equipment &ndash; any grease will deflate the 
  meringue,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;My Nan taught me to wipe out the bowls and the 
  equipment with vinegar.&rdquo; Pre-heat the oven to 130C. You need 200g of egg 
  whites at room temperature and 400g of good quality white caster sugar. &ldquo;If 
  your eggs weigh in at 195g or 210g, don&rsquo;t worry, just double this weight for 
  the sugar content&rdquo;, says Lynn. &ldquo;Meringues are pure chemistry: sugar and egg 
  white in a ratio of 2 to 1. Weigh the egg white as well as the sugar &ndash; you 
  can&rsquo;t go wrong.&rdquo;
</p>
<p>
Put the egg whites and sugar in a heat-proof bowl, stir to remove any lumps, 
  and place over a saucepan of just-boiling water. Make sure the bottom of the 
  basin does not touch the water. Leave over the water for around eight to 10 
  minutes, stirring occasionally and checking that the sugar has melted. 
  Transfer to a mixing bowl to whisk. 
</p>
<p>
Set a timer for 10 minutes. Using an electric whisk, beat for five minutes and 
  then add seeds scraped from one vanilla pod and a few drops of vanilla 
  essence. Continue beating and feel the bowl as you go: it will cool as the 
  air is beaten into the mixture. 
</p>
<p>
After eight minutes, take the beaters out of the meringue and see if it holds 
  its shape. If it isn&rsquo;t stiff, then beat for a further two minutes, and test 
  again before using the mixture. &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t over-beat the meringue &ndash; it should be 
  glossy like a gloss paint and not dull,&rdquo; says Lynn. Transfer the meringue 
  mix on to a large lined baking tray. Quickly work the meringue mixture into 
  a round &ndash; &ldquo;Approximately 200mm circumference so it is still nice and deep,&rdquo; 
  says Lynn &ndash; and make a shallow well in the middle. Put into the preheated 
  oven and then immediately turn the temperature down to 110C. 
</p>
<p>
Cook for three hours. Check that the meringue is firm on the base by gently 
  easing it off the tray and tapping it. If at any point you think the 
  meringue is going to &ldquo;give&rdquo;, stop and cook for a further 30 minutes. Once 
  you are happy that it sounds dull (this means it is still &ldquo;gooey&rdquo; inside) 
  and the base is firm, turn the oven off. 
</p>
<p>
<b>Pastry</b>
</p>
<p>
Some of us might reach for the ready-made stuff out of the supermarket freezer 
  section, but Gerhard Jenne of London-based bakers Konditor &amp; Cook insists 
  that making sweet pastry is literally as easy as one, two, three. &ldquo;The 
  recipe we use is very basic, it&rsquo;s the 1-2-3 method: one part sugar, two 
  parts butter and three parts flour. You don&rsquo;t even need scales. If you want 
  to make it a bit finer, you could also add an egg yolk,&rdquo; says Gerhard. 
</p>
<p>
&ldquo;The most important thing is the sugar itself,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;Never use granulated 
  sugar, it&rsquo;s too coarse and can taste a bit gritty. When you bake it the 
  grains go &lsquo;splodgy&rsquo;.&rdquo; He recommends using good caster sugar, or, for a 
  really fine pastry, icing sugar. Pastry is never going to be a health food, 
  and Gerhard refuses to skimp on the salt, suggesting that you should add it 
  or use salted butter to bring out the flavour. 
</p>
<p>
If you&rsquo;re using egg yolk, start with the sugar and yolk, add the grease and 
  then the flour. You can mix it by hand, which Gerhard insists is quite easy 
  to do, although they use a food processor. &ldquo;It comes together fairly 
  quickly, but once it is together, you don&rsquo;t want to overwork it &ndash; do it 
  fairly speedily,&rdquo; says Gerhard. Once you&rsquo;ve got a nice dough, don&rsquo;t mess 
  about: wrap it in clingfilm and pop it in the fridge to chill for half an 
  hour. 
</p>
<p>
Once you&rsquo;ve taken it out of the fridge, &ldquo;knead it or work it over a couple of 
  times &ndash; it won&rsquo;t need much, pastry is pretty pliable. Then roll it out with 
  as little flour as possible. You don&rsquo;t want a residue, it won&rsquo;t look very 
  nice,&rdquo; he adds.
</p>
<p>
A common problem with pastry that often it is not cooked properly. Gerhard 
  recommends quite a hot oven, of between 180C and 200C, depending on the size 
  of your dish. &ldquo;Cook it until it is golden &ndash; there&rsquo;s nothing worse than 
  undercooked, pale pastry, it&rsquo;s a bit insipid.&rdquo;
</p>
<p>
<b>White sauce</b>
</p>
<p>
A white sauce, or bchamel to give it its more intimidating name, is the 
  classic base for many a sauce. Top chef Paul Gayler, whose book Sauce is 
  dedicated to the art of making a great sauce, tells us how to get it 
  lump-free. 
</p>
<p>
Start by halving a small onion and stud each half with two cloves. Place in a 
  pan with 600ml of full-fat milk and a small bay leaf. &ldquo;The onion, cloves and 
  bay leaf infuse the milk, making it aromatic,&rdquo; says Paul. Bring the milk to 
  the boil and simmer gently for four to five minutes. 
</p>
<p>
In another pan, make a roux. Begin by melting 45g of butter and add 45g of 
  plain flour. Cook for 30 to 40 seconds, stirring frequently, until the roux 
  is pale yellow. &ldquo;Make sure you have equal amounts of butter and flour so you 
  get a nice smoothness. If you have too much flour, it&rsquo;ll be sandy and never 
  cook out.&rdquo;
</p>
<p>
Put the milk through a fine strainer, then beat it vigorously into the roux, 
  and stir until the sauce is smooth. &ldquo;Using a wooden spoon to stir it gives 
  it a lovely silky appearance &ndash; and you can slap the sauce up against the 
  sides!&rdquo; says Paul. 
</p>
<p>
Slowly bring the bchamel to the boil, reduce the heat, and then simmer it for 
  20 minutes, beating occasionally, until the sauce is smooth and glossy. 
  &ldquo;Cook it nice and slowly. You need to simmer it, to allow the flour to cook 
  out. Stick it in the blender if it goes wrong, if it&rsquo;s too lumpy, a blender 
  will bring it back,&rdquo; he says.
</p>

